e, neck, or body.","German: nickname for a simple-minded person, from Middle Low German <i>lappe</i> ‘fool’. This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also 1 above) is also found in France (mainly Alsace, also Lorraine).","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lappe</i> ‘burdock’, perhaps for someone with a prickly character."]}]},{"name":"Samuel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Raj, Varughese, Ashok, Babu, Eapen, Mathai, Saji, Aleykutty, Arul, Arun, Asha, Beena.","English, Scottish, Welsh, German, Dutch, Spanish, French, Slovak, Czech, Jewish, and African (mainly Nigeria and Ethiopia); Hungarian (<b>Sámuel</b>): from the Biblical personal name <i>Samuel</i> (Hebrew <i>Shemuel</i> ‘Name of God’). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages such as Greek patronymic <b>Samouelidis</b>. The name <i>Samuel</i> is also found among Christians in southern India, but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."],"variants":[{"name":"Moilanen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Finnish Eino, Oiva, Jaana, Rauha, Reino, Toivo, Tyyne, Waino, Wiljo, Yalmer.","Finnish: from the Karelian personal name <i>Moila</i> (a form of   Samuel  ) + the suffix <i>-nen</i>. This is aneastern Finnish surname dating back to the 16th century."]},{"name":"Samu","meanings":["Hungarian (also <b>Sámu</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Sámuel</i>; see   Samuel  .","Indian: unexplained.","African (mainly Sierra Leone, Malawi, and Zimbabwe): unexplained."]},{"name":"Samec","meanings":["Czech and Slovak: from <i>samec</i> ‘male’ (an animal), probably used as a nickname for a strong, energetic man.","Czech: possibly also from a pet form of the personal name   Samuel  .","Slovenian: nickname for a loner or topographic name for someone who lived in a secluded spot, from <i>samec</i> ‘loner, solitary person’, also ‘bachelor’. Alternatively, it may be from <i>samec</i> ‘male’ (an animal); compare Czech and Slovak name above."]},{"name":"Sammis","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the personal name   Samuel  ."]},{"name":"Samuels","meanings":["English and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Samuel  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Samel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Moshe, Yetta.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Samuel  ."]},{"name":"Samek","meanings":["Czech: from a pet form of the personal name   Samuel  ."]},{"name":"Samuelian","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Armenian Hagop, Haroutune, Hovsep, Kourken, Siranoush, Souren, Vartan, Vartkes.  French Arsene, Marielle.","Armenian: patronymic from the personal name   Samuel  , a western Armenian variant of <i>Samvel</i>. This form of the surname is found mainly in the US (and also in Lebanon and France); in Armenia it is spelled <b>Samvelyan</b>."]},{"name":"Samelson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Kalmen, Moty, Pinchas.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name   Samuel  ."]},{"name":"Samuelsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Sig, Thor.  German Gunter.","Danish and Norwegian: patronymic from the personal name   Samuel  ."]}]},{"name":"Cadfael","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>mael</i> ‘prince’. The detective monk Brother Cadfael features in a series of novels by  Ellis Peters ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Cadfael Ynad Ap Samuel was born in 1160, in Montgomeryshire, Wales, his father, Samuel ap Cadafael Ynfyd, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. Samuel ap Cadafael Ynfyd, was 21. He had at least 1 son wi